<br>
1.) Add  an /ooc channel to FV. It sounds like a good idea on paper to not allow an /ooc channel on the RP server, but we all know that everyone just uses /shout instead. If there were an /ooc channel, people might actually restrict their zone-wide /ooc chatting to a single channel. Which means those of us who get tired of hearing it can blissfully filter it out, while still being able to hear important things like train messages in /shout. This also eliminates the debate over /shout range.<br>
<br>
2.) Alignments. Hmm. I think the previous poster who suggested that cross-alignment groups should be allowed, but an exp. penalty would be in affect had the right idea. I think the no good&amp;evil groups rule was a bit over the top, because it regulates <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>how</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> people are allowed to roleplay. There can be perfectly good IC reasons why a person would want to group with someone of a significantly different alignment. For buffs, a similar compromise could be used. Most spells get more powerful as you gain levels. Buffs cast on other alignments would be adjusted as if they were cast at a lower-level, depending on how great the alignment difference is. Level-restricted buffs could be even more restrictive when the target is of an opposite alignment. As has been pointed out, alignment combinations would need to be fixed, and faction would need to integrated into alignment.<br>
<br>
3.) No-drop needs to be treated like it is on other servers. I enjoy the convenience of not having it around, for the most part, but I never have understood how that's supposed to enhance RPing. The raid exploit needs to be fixed, though probably not nerfed entirely. There should be some wiggle room for large raids that cover a larger experience range than a typical group would, but forming a two-man raid of a L1 druid and a L55 paladin just to farm the crap out of a 30-ish zone is clearly an abuse<br>
<br>
4.) Naming - yeah, they need to police this better. While they're at it, let's police some of these dye jobs! Yeeech! (j/k about the dye)<br>
<br>
5.) Languages - this one is a bit tougher. I think the 1 point per hour thing was definitely overboard. Perhaps they should just adjust the skill-ups table so that you can't spam a language to 100% in 15 minutes with just one person teaching it. And just for RP purposes, it might be a good idea if you can't learn non-native languages to more than say, 80%. Enough that you can understand it and be understood, but you still have a little bit of an &quot;accent&quot;.<br>
<br>
That's all I can think of, atm. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=blaysethunderwraith>Blayse Thunderwraith</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/23/03 9:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3840.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Dai Ryu is right</span><hr size=1> When I was born, there were certain rules that the Gods had us all follow.  I liked those rules.  The banning of those of good and pure hearts from hunting WITH those of evil rather than trying to stop their nefarious schemes was a wonderful thing indeed.  Unfortunately, our Gods have seen fit to take away the true purpose of doing our jobs correctly in the lands.  (because since they took out the alignments, I get called a freak, a racist, and much much worse... we are role players... I say we need to bring back the alignments, because if I hear &quot;But I'm a GOOD Shadowknight&quot; one more time, I'm going to puke)<br>
